\section{Executive Summary}
This report details the second-year progress of the cybersecurity project aimed
at assessing and fortifying the security posture of the Distributed Digital
Control System (DDCS) in the Prototype Fast Breeder Reactor (PFBR). The
collaborative effort between Birla Institute of Technology, Mesra (BITM) and the
Indira Gandhi Centre for Atomic Research (IGCAR), Kalpakkam encompasses four
interdependent pillars:

\begin{enumerate}
 \item A detailed architectural review of the \textbf{DDCS three-tier
structure} with identification of critical attack surfaces unique to nuclear
control infrastructure.
 \item The design and full operational deployment of an open-source
\textbf{Intrusion Detection and Prevention System (IDPS)} built upon Suricata
and the Elastic Stack (Elasticsearch, Kibana, Filebeat).
 \item The development and deployment of a \textbf{Secure Linux Kiosk
Architecture} for terminal-controlled access to IGCAR operations, significantly
reducing the internal attack surface.
 \item A thorough vulnerability assessment of the \textbf{MySQL database
layer} underpinning DDCS data management, with a complete hardening guide.
\end{enumerate}

Key achievements include a fully operational IDPS pipeline generating near-real-time EVE JSON alerts, a working kiosk system with mouse lockdown and application
launch controls on RHEL 6, and documented mitigation strategies for all major
MySQL vulnerability classes. The outcomes set a robust foundation for continued
hardening and transition to active prevention mode in Year Two.

