\section{Introduction}
\subsection{Project Background}
The rapid evolution of cyber threats poses significant risks to critical
infrastructure systems such as nuclear reactors, which demand highly secure
digital control mechanisms. The DDCS of the PFBR plays a crucial role in
operational safety and efficiency, necessitating a robust cybersecurity strategy
to mitigate threats ranging from malware to Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs).
The increasing reliance on interconnected systems and digital technologies in
critical sectors makes them attractive targets for malicious actors. This
project addresses these challenges by integrating open-source detection
technologies, database security hardening, a controlled-access kiosk interface,
and custom signature development tailored to the unique operational requirements
of nuclear infrastructure.

\subsection{Objectives}
\begin{enumerate}
 \item Identify and document vulnerabilities in the DDCS of PFBR, with a
focused analysis of the MySQL database layer.
 \item Deploy and validate an open-source IDPS (Suricata + Elastic Stack) for
real-time threat detection and network security monitoring.
 \item Implement a secure Linux kiosk system on RHEL 6 to restrict
unauthorized physical and logical access to IGCAR workstations.
 \item Strengthen the overall cybersecurity framework of PFBR through
defense-in-depth strategies combining all the above pillars.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Strategic Importance}
With nuclear facilities being high-value targets for state-sponsored
cyberattacks, securing PFBR's DDCS is essential for national safety and energy
resilience. This project aligns with global cybersecurity standards---GDPR,
HIPAA, and India's DPDP Act---and contributes to advancing protective measures
for critical national infrastructure.

