\section{Intrusion Detection and Prevention System (IDPS): Architecture and
Deployment}
This chapter presents the complete architecture, component rationale, deployment
procedures, and operational guidelines for the open-source IDPS solution built
upon Suricata and the Elastic Stack. This system serves as the primary real-time
threat detection and network security monitoring platform for the PFBR DDCS
environment.

\subsection{Foundational Concepts}
\subsubsection{The Evolving Threat Landscape}
Traditional perimeter defenses are no longer sufficient to protect against the
full spectrum of sophisticated threats. Modern enterprise networks are porous,
with a dissolving perimeter due to cloud adoption, remote work, and
interconnected supply chains. An IDPS fills the gap that conventional firewalls
cannot: it inspects the \textit{content} of allowed traffic and can detect
threats originating from within the network perimeter.
\begin{itemize}
 \item An \textbf{Intrusion Detection System (IDS)} monitors network events
and raises alerts on suspicious activity.
 \item An \textbf{Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)} extends IDS capabilities
by actively blocking detected threats---dropping malicious packets or resetting
connections.
 \item An \textbf{IDPS} is the hybrid form; the Suricata engine deployed here
supports both modes, allowing a controlled transition from passive detection to
active prevention.
\end{itemize}

\begin{notebox}
The system is deployed initially in \textbf{passive IDS mode} to build baseline
confidence and tune rules before enabling active prevention. A misconfigured IPS
blocking legitimate reactor control traffic represents an unacceptable
operational risk in the PFBR environment.
\end{notebox}

\subsubsection{Core Detection Methodologies}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Signature-Based Detection:} Compares traffic against a
database of known malicious patterns. Highly effective with low false positives
for documented threats; cannot detect novel zero-day attacks.
 \item \textbf{Anomaly-Based Detection:} Establishes a behavioral baseline
and flags significant deviations. Can detect previously unknown threats; prone
to false positives. Machine learning is most impactful in this area.
 \item \textbf{Stateful Protocol Analysis:} Compares observed traffic against
standard protocol specifications (HTTP, SMB, DNS). Detects attacks that abuse or
violate protocol structures even without a matching signature.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Deployment Taxonomy}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Network-Based IDPS (NIDS):} Deployed at strategic network
points to monitor traffic across entire subnets. The architecture in this report
is a NIDS implementation using Suricata.
 \item \textbf{Host-Based IDPS (HIDS):} Installed on individual critical
hosts (e.g., database servers) to monitor internal system activities.
Recommended as a complementary layer.
 \item \textbf{Wireless IDPS (WIPS):} Monitors wireless protocol traffic for
rogue access points and unauthorized devices.
 \item \textbf{Network Behavior Analysis (NBA):} Examines traffic flows and
communication patterns; particularly effective for detecting DDoS and C2
traffic.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{System Architecture and Component Roles}
\subsubsection{End-to-End Data Flow}
\begin{enumerate}
 \item \textbf{Detection:} Suricata captures and inspects raw packets on the
monitoring interface (TAP or SPAN port), applying its rulesets and detection
logic.
 \item \textbf{Generation:} On detecting a noteworthy event---alert, HTTP
transaction, DNS query---Suricata generates a structured log entry in unified
\textbf{EVE JSON} format written to \texttt{/var/log/suricata/eve.json}.
 \item \textbf{Collection \& Forwarding:} Filebeat tails the
\texttt{eve.json} file continuously, parses entries via the built-in Suricata
module, and securely forwards them to Elasticsearch.
 \item \textbf{Storage \& Analysis:} Elasticsearch indexes and stores the
event data, enabling high-speed querying, correlation, and complex analytics.
 \item \textbf{Visualization \& Investigation:} Security analysts interact
with Kibana dashboards to investigate alerts, hunt for threats, build
visualizations, and manage incident cases.
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Component Summary}
\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.3}
\begin{tabular}{|l|p{3.5cm}|p{7cm}|}
\hline
\textbf{Component} & \textbf{Primary Role} & \textbf{Key Function} \\ \hline
Suricata & Threat Detection Engine & Deep packet inspection; protocol parsing
(HTTP, DNS, TLS); EVE JSON alert generation \\ \hline
Filebeat & Log Shipper & Tails \texttt{eve.json}; parses via Suricata module;
forwards events to Elasticsearch \\ \hline
Elasticsearch & Data Store \& Analytics & Indexes and stores events; distributed
querying and aggregation for real-time analytics \\ \hline
Kibana & Visualization \& UI & Dashboards, threat hunting workflows, alert
triage, SIEM case management \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{IDPS Component Roles and Responsibilities}
\end{table}

\subsection{Suricata: Key Capabilities}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Multi-threaded Architecture:} Utilizes multiple CPU cores
simultaneously, enabling inspection of high traffic volumes without performance
degradation.
 \item \textbf{Deep Packet Inspection (DPI):} Examines packet payloads, not
just headers. Native high-performance parsers for HTTP, DNS, TLS/SSL, SMB, FTP,
and many others.
 \item \textbf{EVE JSON Output:} A unified JSON format consolidating all
event types---alerts, HTTP transactions, DNS queries, TLS details, file
metadata, flow data---into a single parseable stream. This is the critical
integration point with the Elastic Stack.
 \item \textbf{Operational Flexibility:} Runs as passive IDS, active in-line
IPS, or Network Security Monitoring (NSM) mode for comprehensive logging.
\end{itemize}
\subsection{Automated Setup Using Provided Scripts}
Rather than performing manual step-by-step installation, a fully automated
script-based deployment system has been developed and tested for this project.
All required scripts are placed in the same working directory before execution.

\subsubsection{Script Inventory}
\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.4}
\begin{tabular}{|l|p{9cm}|}
\hline
\textbf{Script File} & \textbf{Purpose} \\ \hline
\texttt{setup\_script.sh} & Master entry-point. Checks prerequisites, system
RAM, and orchestrates the installation of both the SIEM and Suricata. \\ \hline
\texttt{siem\_setup.sh} & Installs and configures Elasticsearch 7.17.13, Kibana,
and Filebeat with mutual TLS certificates. \\ \hline
\texttt{suricata\_setup.sh} & Installs Suricata from the OISF PPA, applies
\texttt{suricata\_temp.yaml}, fetches seven rule sources via
\texttt{suricata-update}, and connects Filebeat. \\ \hline
\texttt{suricata\_temp.yaml} & Pre-configured Suricata YAML template covering
all
protocol parsers, EVE JSON output, and ICS-relevant protocol groups (Modbus,
DNP3, ENIP). \\ \hline
\texttt{change\_interface.sh} & Changes the monitored network interface in
\texttt{suricata.yaml} without editing the file manually. \\ \hline
\texttt{change\_to\_ips.sh} & Switches Suricata from passive IDS mode to active
inline IPS mode using NFQUEUE and configures iptables firewall with
Elasticsearch heap sizing. \\ \hline
\texttt{change\_to\_ids.sh} & Reverts Suricata back to default passive IDS mode
