\subsubsection{Kibana: The Analyst's Window into the Network}
Kibana is the graphical front-end of the Elastic Stack. It does not detect or
store anything itself; instead, it reads the alert data that Filebeat has shipped
into Elasticsearch and presents it as searchable tables, charts, and dashboards.
In simple terms, Suricata is the \emph{sensor}, Elasticsearch is the
\emph{filing cabinet}, and Kibana is the \emph{reading room} where an analyst
actually looks at what was found. Everything an operator does---triaging alerts,
searching for a suspicious IP address, or building a report---happens in this
web interface.

\paragraph{Step~A --- Open Kibana in a web browser.}
Kibana is served over HTTPS on network port \texttt{5601}.
\begin{stepbox}{A --- Reach the Kibana login page}
\begin{enumerate}
 \item On any workstation that can reach the SIEM server over the network, open
a standard web browser (Firefox, Chrome, or Edge).
 \item In the address bar, type the server address followed by the Kibana port:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Kibana web address]
https://<SERVER_IP>:5601        # [change this]: use your SIEM server's IP
\end{lstlisting}
Replace \texttt{<SERVER\_IP>} with the IP address of the machine on which the
SIEM was installed. \textbf{If you are sitting at the SIEM server itself}, you
may instead use \texttt{https://localhost:5601}.
 \item The browser may warn that the certificate is self-signed. This is
expected for an internally generated TLS certificate; choose \emph{Advanced} and
proceed to the site.
\end{enumerate}
\end{stepbox}

