\paragraph{Anatomy of a rule.}
Every rule follows the same grammar. Consider a representative line similar to
those shown in Figure~\ref{fig:local_rules}:
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={A single Suricata rule, broken down in the text below}]
alert tcp $HOME_NET 9090 (msg:"INTERNAL: TCP SYN flood on port 9090"; \
      flags:S; flow:to_server; threshold:type both, track by_src, \
      count 10, seconds 3; sid:30000002; rev:1;)
\end{lstlisting}
It is read left to right in two halves---the \textbf{header} and the
\textbf{options} (everything inside the parentheses):
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{alert} --- the \textbf{action}. In IDS mode this raises an alert;
in IPS mode \texttt{drop} would discard the packet.
 \item \texttt{tcp} --- the \textbf{protocol} to inspect (also \texttt{udp},
\texttt{icmp}, \texttt{http}, \texttt{dns}, etc.).
 \item \texttt{\$HOME\_NET 9090} --- the \textbf{source} network and port. Note
that \texttt{\$HOME\_NET} is a variable defined in \texttt{suricata.yaml}
(covered next), not a fixed address.
 \item \texttt{msg} --- the message shown in Kibana; this is the text that
appears in the \emph{Alert Signature} column.
 \item \texttt{flags:S}, \texttt{flow:to\_server}, \texttt{threshold:\dots} ---
the \textbf{matching conditions} that must all be true for the rule to fire.
 \item \texttt{sid} --- the \textbf{Signature ID}, a number that must be unique.
Keep all locally written rules in a reserved range (this project uses
\texttt{30000000+}) so they never clash with downloaded rulesets.
 \item \texttt{rev} --- the \textbf{revision number}. Increment it by one every
time you edit an existing rule so the change is tracked.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Applying rule changes safely.}
After editing, always validate the configuration \emph{before} reloading; a
single malformed rule can otherwise stop the engine from starting.
\begin{cmdbox}{suricata -T \ldots\ then live reload}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption={Test rules, then reload without downtime}]
# 1. Test the full configuration and all rules (no changes are applied)
sudo suricata -T -c /etc/suricata/suricata.yaml -v
# 2. If the test reports success, reload rules live -- no restart, no lost packets
sudo kill -USR2 $(pidof suricata)
\end{lstlisting}
\end{cmdbox}

\begin{warningbox}
Never reload or restart Suricata immediately after editing rules without running
the \texttt{-T} test first. If the test prints an error, fix the offending rule
\emph{before} reloading---in the PFBR DDCS environment an engine that fails to
start means a loss of monitoring coverage.
\end{warningbox}

