\section{Secure Linux Kiosk Architecture on RHEL 6}
\subsection{Overview and Security Rationale}
A major deliverable of this project is the development of a \textbf{Secure Linux
Kiosk System} deployed on Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 (RHEL 6) workstations
within the IGCAR facility. The kiosk restricts what an operator can do at a
workstation to a predefined, auditable set of actions, significantly reducing
the risk of insider threats, accidental misconfiguration, and unauthorized
software execution.

The design philosophy is rooted in the principle of \textbf{least privilege}: an
operator at a DDCS terminal should have access to only the specific applications
required for their role---no desktop, no browser, no arbitrary file system
access. The kiosk intercepts the login session and presents a controlled
terminal-based menu instead of a standard desktop environment.

\subsubsection{Security Objectives of the Kiosk}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Restrict Application Execution:} Only pre-approved
applications (Wireshark, procom00, CR\_DS) can be launched.
 \item \textbf{Disable Peripheral Input:} The mouse is disabled at all times
outside of an active approved application, eliminating panel-clicking and
accidental GUI interactions.
 \item \textbf{Prevent Session Escape:} Standard interrupt signals
(\texttt{SIGINT}, \texttt{SIGTERM}, \texttt{SIGTSTP}) are trapped so that
Ctrl+C, Ctrl+Z, and Ctrl+\textbackslash{} cannot be used to break out of the
kiosk.
 \item \textbf{Enforce Fullscreen:} Launched applications are forced to
fullscreen and pinned above all other windows using \texttt{wmctrl}, preventing
window manager interaction.
 \item \textbf{Controlled File Operations:} File management is limited to
create, copy, and move operations through the kiosk menu---no arbitrary deletion
or execution.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{System Architecture of the Kiosk Script}
The kiosk is implemented as a Bash shell script (\texttt{final\_kiosk.sh}) that
is invoked automatically at login by modifying the user's
\texttt{.bash\_profile}. The script operates in a continuous loop until the
operator chooses to exit.

\subsubsection{Key Functional Modules}
