\subsection{Detailed Command-by-Command Explanation}
This section explains every significant command and construct in the kiosk
script, describing both its technical function and its security role.

\subsubsection{Signal Trapping}
\begin{cmdbox}{trap '' SIGINT SIGTERM SIGTSTP}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
trap '' SIGINT SIGTERM SIGTSTP
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:} The \texttt{trap} command intercepts OS signals sent to
the shell process. By assigning an empty string \texttt{''} as the handler, the
signal is silently ignored rather than acted upon.
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{SIGINT} is sent when the user presses \textbf{Ctrl+C}. Without
this trap, Ctrl+C would terminate the kiosk loop.
 \item \texttt{SIGTERM} is sent by \texttt{kill} or process managers. This
trap prevents external processes from terminating the kiosk.
 \item \texttt{SIGTSTP} is sent when the user presses \textbf{Ctrl+Z}.
Without this trap, the operator could suspend the kiosk and gain raw shell
access.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Security impact:} Eliminates the three most common keyboard-based
methods of escaping a restricted shell environment.
\end{cmdbox}

\subsubsection{Mouse Discovery and Control}
\begin{cmdbox}{xinput list | grep | sed}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
function get_mouse_ids() {
  xinput list | grep "slave pointer" \
  | sed -n 's/.*id=\([0-9]*\).*/\1/p'
}
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{xinput list} queries the X11 input subsystem and prints all
connected input devices along with their numeric IDs.
  \item \texttt{grep "slave pointer"} filters the output to retain only
pointer (mouse) devices, discarding keyboards and other inputs.
  \item \texttt{sed -n
's/.*id=\textbackslash([0-9]*\textbackslash).*/\textbackslash1/p'}
uses a regular expression to extract just the numeric ID from each matching
line.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Why dynamic detection:} Hardcoding mouse IDs (e.g., \texttt{xinput
disable 8}) would fail if the device enumeration changes on reboot or if a USB
mouse is swapped. Dynamic discovery ensures the lockdown is robust across
hardware changes.
\end{cmdbox}

\begin{cmdbox}{xinput disable / xinput enable}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
function disable_mouse() {
  for id in $(get_mouse_ids); do
  xinput disable "$id" 2>/dev/null
  done
}
function enable_mouse() {
  for id in $(get_mouse_ids); do
 xinput enable "$id" 2>/dev/null
 done
}
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:} Iterates over every discovered mouse device ID and
disables or enables it individually in the X11 input layer. The
\texttt{2>/dev/null} suppression discards any error output (e.g., if a device
was unplugged mid-operation).

\textbf{Security impact:} A disabled mouse device still exists in the X11 device
tree but all movement and click events from it are discarded. The operator
cannot click on the taskbar, open a terminal, or interact with any GUI element
outside of an authorized application session.
\end{cmdbox}

\subsubsection{Application Launcher}
\begin{cmdbox}{launch\_app() -- eval, wmctrl, blocking execution}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
function launch_app() {
  local app_name="$1"
  local app_command="$2"
  enable_mouse
  # Background watchdog: force the new window to fullscreen
  (
  sleep 1
  if type wmctrl >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  wmctrl -r :ACTIVE: -b add,fullscreen,above
  fi
  ) &
  WATCHDOG_PID=$!
  # Launch the app -- BLOCKING: script waits here until app closes
  eval "$app_command"
  # Cleanup
  kill $WATCHDOG_PID 2>/dev/null
  disable_mouse
  # Force focus back to kiosk terminal
  if type wmctrl >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  wmctrl -r :ACTIVE: -b add,fullscreen
  fi
}
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{Command breakdown:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{local app\_name="\$1"} and \texttt{local app\_command="\$2"}
--- The \texttt{local} keyword scopes these variables to the function only,
preventing them from leaking into the global shell environment.
  \item \texttt{enable\_mouse} --- Restores mouse input so the operator can
use the GUI application normally.
  \item The subshell \texttt{( sleep 1; wmctrl ... ) \&} runs a background
process. It waits 1 second (for the application window to appear), then uses
\texttt{wmctrl} to force the active window to fullscreen and always-on-top. The
\texttt{\&} sends it to the background so the main script continues.
  \item \texttt{WATCHDOG\_PID=\$!} --- Captures the process ID of the
background watchdog so it can be cleaned up after the application exits.
  \item \texttt{wmctrl -r :ACTIVE: -b add,fullscreen,above} --- Applies two
window manager hints to the currently active window: \texttt{fullscreen}
(removes decorations and fills the screen) and \texttt{above} (keeps it on top
of all other windows).
  \item \texttt{eval "\$app\_command"} --- Executes the application command
string. The script \textbf{blocks here} until the application process
terminates. This is the key mechanism that prevents the operator from returning
to the kiosk menu while an app is open.
  \item \texttt{kill \$WATCHDOG\_PID 2>/dev/null} --- Terminates the
background watchdog process if it has not already exited.
 \item \texttt{disable\_mouse} --- Immediately re-locks the mouse when
control returns to the kiosk menu.
\end{itemize}
\end{cmdbox}

\begin{cmdbox}{type wmctrl >/dev/null 2>\&1}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
if type wmctrl >/dev/null 2>&1; then
 wmctrl -r :ACTIVE: -b add,fullscreen,above
fi
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:} \texttt{type wmctrl} checks whether the \texttt{wmctrl}
binary is installed and available in the PATH, sending all output to
\texttt{/dev/null}. If \texttt{wmctrl} is absent, the block is skipped
gracefully rather than causing a fatal error. This makes the kiosk resilient on
systems where \texttt{wmctrl} has not yet been installed.
\end{cmdbox}

\subsubsection{File Operations Module}
\begin{cmdbox}{touch, cp, mv -- controlled file access}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
case $fchoice in
 1) read -p "Filename to create: " f; touch "$f" 2>/dev/null ;;
 2) read -p "Source: " s; read -p "Destination: " d; cp -r "$s" "$d" ;;
 3) read -p "Source: " s; read -p "Destination: " d; mv "$s" "$d" ;;
 4) return ;;
esac
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{touch "\$f"} --- Creates an empty file with the given name.
Existing files are not overwritten; only the timestamp is updated.
 \item \texttt{cp -r "\$s" "\$d"} --- Copies a file or directory recursively
from source to destination. The \texttt{-r} flag handles directories.
 \item \texttt{mv "\$s" "\$d"} --- Moves or renames a file or directory.
 \item \texttt{return} --- Exits the sub-menu loop and returns execution to
the main kiosk menu.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Security note:} Notably, \texttt{rm} (delete) is \textit{not} included.
Operators can create, copy, and move files but cannot delete them. Deletion must
go through an administrator, ensuring data cannot be inadvertently or
maliciously destroyed from the kiosk.
\end{cmdbox}

\subsubsection{Print Module}
\begin{cmdbox}{lp -- CUPS print command}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
lp -n "$nc1" $opts "$f1"
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:} \texttt{lp} is the CUPS (Common UNIX Printing System)
command-line print utility.
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{-n "\$nc1"} --- Specifies the number of copies to print.
 \item \texttt{-d \$pnam1} (from \texttt{\$opts}) --- Directs the job to a
named printer. If omitted, the default printer is used.
 \item \texttt{-o landscape} or \texttt{-o portrait} --- Sets page
orientation.
 \item \texttt{-o sides=two-sided-long-edge} --- Enables double-sided
printing.
 \item \texttt{"\$f1"} --- The file to print. The module first checks
\texttt{[ ! -f "\$f1" ]} (file does not exist) and exits gracefully rather than
sending an invalid job to the printer.
\end{itemize}
\end{cmdbox}
\subsubsection{Time-of-Day Greeting}
\begin{cmdbox}{date -- system clock and greeting logic}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
current_time=$(date +%H)
display_date=$(date +"%d-%m-%Y %H:%M:%S")
if [ "$current_time" -ge 5 ] && [ "$current_time" -le 12 ]; then
 echo " Good Morning !"
elif [ "$current_time" -gt 12 ] && [ "$current_time" -le 16 ]; then
 echo " Good Afternoon !"
elif [ "$current_time" -gt 16 ] && [ "$current_time" -le 18 ]; then
 echo " Good Evening !"
else echo " Good Night !"
fi
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{What it does:}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{date +\%H} extracts the current hour in 24-hour format
(00--23).
 \item \texttt{date +"\%d-\%m-\%Y \%H:\%M:\%S"} formats the full timestamp as
\texttt{DD-MM-YYYY HH:MM:SS}.
 \item The arithmetic comparisons (\texttt{-ge}, \texttt{-le}, \texttt{-gt})
select the appropriate greeting string based on the hour.
\end{itemize}
\end{cmdbox}

\subsubsection{Main Loop and User Session Control}
\begin{cmdbox}{while true / read -p / case-esac}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash]
while true
do
 clear
 echo " SECURE KIOSK MENU"
 # ... display options ...
 read -p "Enter Choice: " choice
 case $choice in
 1) show_greeting; application_submenu ;;
 2) file_operations_menu ;;
 3) print_file_module ;;
 4) n=$(who | wc -l)
 echo "There are $n users logged onto the system"
 sleep 2 ;;
 5) exit ;;
 *) echo "Invalid Option."; sleep 1 ;;
 esac
done
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{Command breakdown:}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{while true} --- Creates an infinite loop. The kiosk will
return to this menu after every action until the operator explicitly selects
option 5 (Exit).
 \item \texttt{clear} --- Clears the terminal screen at the start of each
loop iteration, preventing previous output from being visible and reducing
information leakage.
 \item \texttt{read -p "Enter Choice: " choice} --- Reads a single line of
input from the operator into the variable \texttt{choice}. The \texttt{-p} flag
displays the prompt inline without a newline.
 \item \texttt{case \$choice in ... esac} --- Pattern-matches the operator's
input against predefined options. Any input not matching a valid option falls
through to the \texttt{*)} wildcard, which prints an error and pauses for 1
second before returning to the menu.
 \item \texttt{who | wc -l} --- \texttt{who} lists all currently logged-in
users (one per line); \texttt{wc -l} counts the lines to give the total number
of active sessions.
 \item \texttt{sleep 2} --- Pauses execution for 2 seconds so the operator
can read the output before the screen is cleared on the next loop iteration.
 \item \texttt{exit} --- Terminates the kiosk script, which---since it is the
user's login shell---logs the operator out of the session entirely.
\end{itemize}
\end{cmdbox}

\subsection{RHEL 6 Environment Setup: Installing Dependencies}
The following commands must be run as root (or with \texttt{sudo}) to prepare
the RHEL 6 system before deploying the kiosk script.

\begin{stepbox}{1 --- Install wmctrl (Window Manager Control)}
\texttt{wmctrl} is required for fullscreen enforcement. On RHEL 6, install it
via the EPEL repository:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Install wmctrl on RHEL 6]
# Enable the EPEL repository first
rpm -ivh https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/6/i386/epel-release-6-8.noarch.rpm
# Install wmctrl
yum install wmctrl -y
# Verify installation
wmctrl --version
\end{lstlisting}
\end{stepbox}

\begin{stepbox}{2 --- Install xinput}
\texttt{xinput} is part of the \texttt{xorg-x11-utils} package on RHEL 6:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Install xinput on RHEL 6]
yum install xorg-x11-utils -y
# Verify xinput can list devices
xinput list
\end{lstlisting}
\end{stepbox}

\begin{stepbox}{3 --- Install CUPS Printing Support}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Install CUPS on RHEL 6]
yum install cups -y
service cups start
chkconfig cups on
# Verify default printer is configured
lpstat -p -d
\end{lstlisting}
\end{stepbox}

\begin{stepbox}{4 --- Deploy the Kiosk Script}
Copy the kiosk script to a system location and make it executable:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Deploy the Kiosk Script]
cp final_kiosk.sh /usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh
chmod 755 /usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh
chown root:root /usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh
\end{lstlisting}
\end{stepbox}

\begin{stepbox}{5 --- Configure Auto-Launch at Login}
To make the kiosk the user's login shell, add it to the operator's
\texttt{.bash\_profile}. Replace \texttt{operator} with the actual username:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Configure Kiosk Auto-Launch]
echo "/usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh" >> /home/operator/.bash_profile
\end{lstlisting}
Alternatively, for a more robust lockdown, change the operator user's login
shell directly:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Set Kiosk as Login Shell (Most
Secure)]
# Add the kiosk script to the list of valid shells
echo "/usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh" >> /etc/shells
# Change the operator's login shell to the kiosk
chsh -s /usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh operator
\end{lstlisting}
\begin{warningbox}
Only use \texttt{chsh} after thoroughly testing the kiosk script. If the script
has an error, the operator account will be locked out and an administrator must
manually restore the shell via \texttt{chsh -s /bin/bash operator} from a root
session.
\end{warningbox}
\end{stepbox}

\begin{stepbox}{6 --- Configure RHEL 6 Auto-Login for the Kiosk User (Optional)}
To make the workstation boot directly into the kiosk without a login prompt,
configure GDM (GNOME Display Manager) automatic login. Edit
\texttt{/etc/gdm/custom.conf}:
\begin{lstlisting}[caption=GDM Auto-Login Configuration]
[daemon]
AutomaticLoginEnable=true
AutomaticLogin=operator
\end{lstlisting}
\begin{notebox}
Auto-login bypasses the GDM password prompt. Use only on physically secured,
dedicated workstations where the kiosk is the sole intended user interface.
\end{notebox}
\end{stepbox}

\begin{stepbox}{7 --- Verify the Kiosk Deployment}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Verification Commands]
# Test the script syntax for errors before deploying
bash -n /usr/local/bin/kiosk.sh
# Run the script interactively as the operator user to test
su - operator
# Check that xinput is correctly discovering mouse IDs
xinput list | grep "slave pointer"
# Confirm wmctrl is functional
wmctrl -l
\end{lstlisting}
\end{stepbox}

