\section{MySQL Database Security: Vulnerabilities and Hardening}
MySQL serves as the underlying data management layer for many DDCS support
systems. Given that databases are the central repositories for the most
sensitive operational and configuration data, a dedicated security assessment
was conducted. This chapter presents findings on MySQL vulnerability classes,
exploitation mechanisms, and the corresponding hardening strategies.

\subsection{Importance of Database Security}
Databases represent the final line of defense for an organization's most
sensitive assets. Global cybersecurity incidents related to database breaches
exceeded \$4.5 trillion in 2025.
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Protects Sensitive Data:} Breaches via SQL injection or
unauthorized access lead to identity theft, fraud, or catastrophic operational
data leaks.
 \item \textbf{Ensures Compliance:} Regulations like GDPR, HIPAA, and India's
DPDP Act carry fines of up to 4\% of annual revenue for violations.
 \item \textbf{Maintains Business Continuity:} Database attacks cause
operational downtime and revenue loss that can cascade into safety incidents in
nuclear environments.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Classification of MySQL Vulnerabilities}
\begin{enumerate}
 \item \textbf{Application-Level Vulnerabilities:} Failures in input handling
at the application layer allow attackers to craft malicious SQL statements via
improperly validated user input fields (OWASP Top 10 \#1).
 \item \textbf{Authentication and Authorization Vulnerabilities:} Weak
password policies, absence of multi-factor authentication, or misconfigured
privilege assignments. Improper GRANT permissions and privilege escalation via
vulnerable stored procedures are the primary vectors.
 \item \textbf{Configuration-Related Exposures:} Insecure defaults in
\texttt{my.cnf}, port 3306 exposed to public networks, SSL/TLS disabled, and
MySQL running as the OS root user.
 \item \textbf{Network-Based Vulnerabilities:} Exposing the MySQL service
over TCP/IP without firewall restrictions turns a backend component into a
public attack vector.
 \item \textbf{Software and Patch-Related Vulnerabilities:} Outdated MySQL
versions with publicly documented CVEs and mature exploit code.
\end{enumerate}

