\subsection{SQL Injection --- Deep Dive}
SQL Injection (SQLi) is the most critical and widely exploited MySQL
vulnerability. It occurs when user-supplied input is directly incorporated into
SQL queries without proper sanitization.

\subsubsection{Common Attack Payloads}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{' OR 1=1 --} --- Authentication bypass.
 \item \texttt{UNION SELECT username, password FROM users} --- Data
extraction.
 \item \texttt{'; DROP TABLE users; --} --- Destructive data deletion.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Mitigation Strategies}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Prepared Statements:} SQL code is pre-compiled with
placeholders; user input is treated as data and can never alter query logic.
 \item \textbf{Parameterized Queries:} Functionally identical to prepared
statements; language-agnostic.
 \item \textbf{Input Validation:} Rejects malicious patterns before they
reach the database. Must complement---not replace---parameterization.
 \item \textbf{Stored Procedures:} Encapsulate business logic with built-in
parameterization, reducing raw SQL attack surface.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Administrative Command Risks}
