\section{Conclusion}
The second year of the IGCAR--BITM cybersecurity collaboration has successfully
delivered a comprehensive and operationally validated security framework for the
PFBR DDCS environment. Three major technical pillars were conceived,
implemented, and tested within the agreed timeline. The open-source IDPS, built
on Suricata and the Elastic Stack, now provides continuous deep packet
inspection and near-real-time threat visibility across the DDCS network. The
Secure Linux Kiosk, deployed on RHEL 6, enforces strict access control at every
operator workstation, eliminating the most prevalent vectors of insider threat
and accidental misconfiguration. The MySQL security assessment has
systematically addressed every major database vulnerability class, producing a
replicable eight-step hardening guide that strengthens the data layer
underpinning DDCS operations.

Collectively, these deliverables establish a layered defense-in-depth posture
spanning the network, host, application, and database tiers of the PFBR DDCS---a
posture that is passive before active, restrictive by default, and resilient
against both external intrusion and insider threat. The project has not only met
but exceeded the deliverables agreed upon between BITM and IGCAR, producing
working deployable systems, detailed operational runbooks, and a strong
technical foundation.

